post2.caption: Dear Maud: Happy Birthday, King! They arrested the devils that took your life last night. Unfortunately, that will NEVER be enough. But, just figured Id update you. People down here keep talking abt justice but how could this ever be fair?Your life shouldnt have been taken in the first place, aint no one gonna be able to make it up not to me at least, but I do hope others can find solace in something. As for me,Ill be haunted forever. I know that becuz the first person I thought of when I learned abt your death was our other brother Trayvon,& then of course I traveled down that list that goes on and on and on and...sigh,once again,Ive been sentenced to nightmares. I know you dont know me, but most days, I run. Today, I couldnt tho. Everyone else ran for you today, but I just wasnt well enough for it. Maybe tomorrow. Today I stayed in bed with you in my head. I tried to watch Netflix & cuddle with you, the way siblings sometimes do, but my internet isnt working. I know,I know! We never met, but we didnt need to. Weve been connected forever, since way back when our great, great, great, great, great, great, great, great,...great grandparents first came [were brutally forced onto ships] to the Americas its the traumatic memory that sealed our bond forever. So let me just say, I miss you. And even if I hadnt met you, I KNEW you, in some capacity. Bcuz bro, your absence? I FEEL it more than people Ive known who have passed. You were different! That was our siblingly resemblance. You ARE special! You had more to do here, I can feel it& anyone who really knows me, knows: I.feel.EVERYTHING. Ill be ok, cuz at least I know you havent really left me.We def gotta finish what you were supposed to do here.But, man! I wish I could have at least hugged you!Maybe you wouldve passed your greatness onto me so Id be more clear on how to continue your legacy. Baby bro,for now,I pledge to never forget you. My existence will make people FEEL and KNOW you.& trust, once my internet start working again, we watching Netflix together.& Im sorry I didnt run today, but every run moving forward will be for you. Im sure you already knew that tho. -Judine

post2.caption: If its hard to get to the shops or your go-to food isnt available where you are right now, I want you to know that you can still create meals that you enjoy using only a few ingredients. Personally, my food is always pretty simple but that does not mean its boring or flavourless. I add oregano, salt, pepper and lemon juice to most of my meals and it makes SUCH a difference, and its so easy! A meal like this could be prepared in literally ten minutes and youll just need pasta, prawns or shrimps (frozen is fine if fresh is not available), tomatoes, spinach (again, frozen is fine if fresh is not available), olive oil, garlic, salt and pepper. This is how Id make it: Cook pasta in boiling, salted water. Heat olive oil and garlic in a pan. Add prawns (or shrimps) to the pan. Once theyre cooked through, add tomatoes and spinach to the pan. Stir until the spinach is wilted, then add drained, cooked pasta and a dash of the pasta water to the pan. Stir through and add salt and pepper. You can also add lemon juice if you have it, and whatever herbs you like! #BBGcommunity, what are you cooking at home at the moment? #BBGathome Photo credit: @saltandlavender

post2.caption: These are my intrinsic motivating factors. In my book I talk about intrinsic vs extrinsic motivation in the context of exercise. Just to briefly explain... INTRINSIC - Looking inward to find reasons to workout for your own sake (see above). EXTRINSIC - Looking outward to find reasons to workout. E.g for others approval, compliments etc. Diet culture thrives off of us engaging in exercise through extrinsic motivation. Thats why it pitches working out as a way to get a beach/ dream body often through short lived bursts of exercise prior to a holiday or as a means of revenge after a break up. It wants us to view exercise as a quick fix so we can buy the products & plans to achieve the ever elusive body goals. Untangling exercise from Diet Culture also means examining where our motivation comes from. I believe by learning about and understanding the physical and psychological benefits of exercise, and then in turn using movement as a form of self care helps to develop your own intrinsic motivation. Most importantly working out for intrinsic reasons leads to long term consistency- which is a key factor in reaping those wonderful benefits of regular activity. Cos thats what we want - you to move your body in a way you enjoy and feel the benefits in mind & body. So with that being said, WHY DO YOU WORKOUT? Do you think its for intrinsic, or extrinsic reasons or perhaps a mix of both? No right or wrong answer P.S Brand new @trainhappypodcast episode out with @beauty_redefined on Spotify & Apple. #TrainHappy

post1.caption: The Romanian Row: Your Essential Home Strength Training Addition During Lockdown we have all been bombarded with endless fitness junk on social media from a long list of unqualified & unexperienced sources, unfortunately thats the fitness industry for you But here is a huge bang for your buck movement that you should be doing both now & for the rest of your life. Why? Postural control Balance work Alignment awareness Isometric Strength Pull Strength The Romanian Row has got it all. This has been one of the main movements I have been working on with my 1:1 clients on zoom PT during lockdown, from using a can of baked beans to 24kg kettlebell it has created a great challenge for all ability levels From a standing position, single leg hinge into a standing T. Shoulder blades pinched, chest line positive and your hips parallel to the ground. Once steady row your desired weight/object for 8 reps before hinging out. Repeat each side for 3 sets and feel that full body switch on! Enjoy the real results from real work (rather than made up exercises from bored celebrities ) #strengthtraining

post0.caption: Sometimes seeing images of places over and over can desensitize you to the rawness of it. We can start to feel like nature is a glorified amusement park... totally safe & sterile. Upon arriving in Milford Sound our experience felt nothing like that. I was actually speechless at how raw it felt. Towering vegetated walls, rough water and really only one way in and out. Regardless of how many people stood on the shore or entered by ship there was still plenty of fun to be had testing yourself against natures will.

post1.caption: Siberian Wind they call it, so cold it will make you want to vomit when your fingers thaw out. Confession...The last time I picked up a camera for proper work was early February. It was northern Japan during a window of dream conditions shooting snowboarding in Hokkaido. We escaped for a day of surfing & were greeted with about as heinous of weather as you could expect, but as always we made the most of it. I can still feel the sting of the cold & hear the whip of the wind. In many ways Im ok with the fact that its been many months since Ive used my so called profession to create an image. Because the ones I have made seem to stick with me for a long time. That is the beauty of rugged & harsh places... the more effort you put in the greater they seem to reward you. It seems silly but I felt a lot of emotion tonight looking back at these images because it brought me so much happiness. The crew, the food, the random 7-11 stops at midnight, the ramen, the language barrier, the frozen fingers, lack of sleep, the onsens. All in the name of creating a story worth sharing. Thanks @billabong @iwanairesort @billabong_snowboarding @bodemerrill for that last assignment - it was a good one!

post2.caption: UPDATE: Today is quarantine day 33 here in New Zealand. I also recently celebrated my 33rd Birthday. While Id normally celebrate by surfing, skating or hiking in the backcountry, this year I spent the day working in the garden behind the kiwi cottage that we are renting. This is how I've spent most days during lockdown. Unlike other parts of the world, NZ has taken the isolation measures extremely seriously. The only stores open are the pharmacy and supermarkets - nothing else. No take-out food. No hardware stores. No hiking or water activities either. Youre not even permitted to get in your car if it isnt to access essential goods. To coincide with the physical isolation my phone decided to stop turning on a while back. While I tend to keep my phone at a distance as it is, this has forced me to fully exist in the present moment, here, and now. (To any friends or family trying to get a hold of me via call or text, please know there is a good chance I havent received it). I like this photo because it is a real moment I want to remember these times. This isnt a breathtaking vista, a perfect wave, or some unique landscape feature. This is real life, in a time Im sure we will all remember for the rest of our lives. Tomorrow the country will begin to reopen and we will start to discover what the new norm of life is like here. Sending good vibes to you all! #NewZealand

post1.caption: We premiered one of my favorite projects of the past year over the weekend. We won a a very cool award. We are so stoked. The project is a short documentary film called Refuge and you will be able to see more than just these frame grabs very soon. Refuge is the story of Piseth Sam (@mightymight88) a woman who came to the United States as a refugee, found her way to Boston thru Seattle and Minneapolis, and is now a strong/vibrant voice in the local outdoor, climbing and LGBTQ communities. To even imagine the range of challenging experiences and emotions she has endured is impossible for me. But what is most incredible is; how positive, supportive, and welcoming she is, in spite of the adversity she has faced. Thank You to @Merrell for supporting diverse and inclusive films about the outdoors. Thank You to the great team that made it possible thank you @camp4collective @merrell @cheynelempe @bchendrix @tarakerzhner @elizleilani @felixkunze

post1.caption: Asking permission is necessary. This is a hot topic for me and one I don't take lightly. There are so many amazing places out there to photograph, and many may have restrictions. I have witnessed seasoned photographers deliberately break rules and disrespect signs that say, "Please stay out, rehabilitation in progress." Being told by the individual while laughing, anything for the shot right Andy?! No, not anything for the shot. We as a community of artists need to respect people's property, signs, and even more so, places that don't have signs. Use common sense. To gain access and destroy precious and fragile ecosystems, or to disrespect the land and/or private property, just to keep up with the rat race, is a disgrace. I had a local guide help me search for a barn and finally came across this one. It was amazing to have full permissible access from the family. I even sent the images to them as a thank you. As you explore this beautiful world, please be respectful. It's sad this has to be reinforced, but reinforced it must. Hold one another accountable, leave a better trace, and remember your with every outing. (A +ONE is any type of a GIVE BACK on every outing you go on. It's on us to do better.)

And to the rest of the world we say, we are not drowning! We are fighting! - Kevin Aipopo Deeply grateful to the entire @pacificclimatewarriors family and to @fentonlutun, Kevin Aipopo, Koreti Tiumalu, for their leadership and vision on the front lines fighting for fight for climate justice, and for trusting us to share a small part of their story; to Lulu, Dobby, Kevika, Bernard and all the families of Tuvalu that welcomed us into their lives and made us feel like family thousands of miles from home; and to @canyonwoodward and @aidanhaley for being such steadfast and brilliant creative conspirators in bringing this short love letter of a film to life. Very excited to get to premier Matagi Mlohi: Strong Winds at @mountainfilm as a part of their Indomitable Spirits shorts (II) program - check their website for virtual passes to the amazing lineup of films that theyre curating and sharing over the course of the next 10 days. post1.caption: As states begin to reopen and the curve begins to flatten in some urban areas, it feels important to remember rural communities that are on a different part of the curve and who (in many cases) are vastly under resourced in terms of access to healthcare and basic necessities. The American Indian tribes and specifically Navajo Nation are getting hit hard by the COVID-19 crisis we are in. On a per capita basis this would place the Navajo Nation in states right behind NY & NJ in terms of per capita impacts. @lennecefer I feel thankful for the time and experiences I have shared with folks on the Navajo nation and on Ute and Hopi lands, and appreciate the opportunity Len and @nativesoutdoors have created to help raise funds to support these communities (link in bio) through vetted resource list for direct donations as well as a print sale of @tarakerzhners beautiful work as the nation moves to put on a face of normalcy, the need for support will likely shift to more rural areas that are both underserviced and under reported on - a dangerous combination I think. staying proactively involved and aware of the needs of communities we care about is more important than ever. I know many folks are struggling in this time but I hope that those of us who can support, do. Hope you all are keeping well. Thanks for reading. (Bio link for more info)

post2.caption: thunder rolls like giant trains, an old dry laugh across the plains; fleeting forms and golden flames. an unnamed peak. a single sigh. a passing of the by and by. now shadows named alone by light, sing their songs once more by night; as you and me and the old grey owl, sit and wonder why and how; between the was and is and might, the here and now come squeeze in tight, to gossip of the coyotes tail, the flustered flurry of the quail. Oh ho! you want a story old, round fires bold, tonight is told. this too passes, this too stays. yet absent darkness there are no rays. salute the dawn and cheer the dusk, the gift of time, lived heart to husk.

post2.caption: ...YOU GUESSED IT! Our second food product is vegan MILK! A SUPER MILK! For years I have mixed protein powders and superfoods into Leas oat/nut milks to up the nutritional content (especially when she goes through phases of being picky with food) and creating a super milk to meet all our family needs has been such a joy! Imagine a shelf-stable, powdered plant-based milk thats extra high in protein, jam packed with vitamins and nutrients, made without strange additives or added sugars - and one that completely eliminates your need to buy cartons of milk from the store? The packaging solution is a big piece for me. Did you know its extremely challenging to completely recycle milk cartons? The cartons of milk you find in the grocery store are generally made of a paperboard/plastic/aluminum layering and most have hard plastic screw-tops. When thrown in a landfill, the paperboard from one single carton takes 5 years to decompose and the plastic, as you know, remains in landfills for 1,000 years. Re-thinking how we consume milk and finding ways to reduce our waste is huge! Im so excited to share this food journey with you! And I cant wait for you to taste this delicious, nutritious, plant based super milk

post1.caption: As a young guy I spent the majority of my time on rugby pitches, in boxing rings, lifting metal plates and running marathons. When I hit the working world with all of it's stresses, I realised that I was spending a disprportinate amount of time with heavily tattooed men that enjoyed punching me. It was then I decided that stepping up my yoga practice could solver two problems. It would help me build a social group that didn't want to watch Rocky re-runs or chat about workplace politics, and I could begin a little self-enquiry at a challenging time in my life, through a daily asana and a meditation practice. The rest is history. " Wise words from London based yoga teacher @adamhusler #boysofyoga

post2.caption: ASANA BREAKDOWN Cow Pose - Bitilasana (bee-tee-lahs-anna) People often mix up cat and cow pose because the way you are instructed is the opposite of the way they're practised. It should really be cow and cat pose! If in doubt act like a scared cat or a mooing cow. HOW TO: 1. From a table top position draw the chest forward and upward, broadening the collarbones as the shoulders draw down the back. 2. Ground the hands into the mat to create the necessary support. 3. Keep the neck in line with the spine. 4. Engage the core, drawing navel to spine, to support lower back flexion. 5. Rotate the sit bones to the sky and the same time as the chest movement to move the lower spine.

post1.caption: Dear Mommy, Thank you for the countless times you took me to, and picked me up from cheerleading practice, piano lessons, and so many other after school activities. Listen, the patience you had with me when I was practicing for my driver's license and I side swiped a mailbox and yelled, "I'm doing the best I can mom!" You responded,"Well, you gonna have to do better than that, child!" It was a real moment. Only a mama as strong as you could legit SAVE MY LIFE when we were riding in your brown Toyota, turning the corner, and the door flew open while you continued driving, while grabbing me by my coat so that didn't fly out.Whew, the 80s/90s were wild. . .. Above all, I'm grateful to have been chosen as your daughter. You were my first best friend and honestly you have always been my definition for mothering and showing me how to properly wear my crown. I love you Mom. Happy Mother's Day.
